## Issue description

Say, I have a pure abstract class (Ancestor).
I implemented a sub class inheriting it (Parent).
For testing purpose, I've implemented another sub class inheriting Parent (Child).

When I create a python binding for a function `std::shared_ptr<Ancestor> CreateChild() { return std::make_shared<Child>(); }` as a name `create_child()`, I expected that

```
create_child().function
```

calls a function of the Child, but by unknown reasons, a function of the class Parent was called, and finally SEGV occurs.


## Reproducible example code

```cpp
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>

#include <memory>

namespace py = pybind11;

class Ancestor {
public:
    virtual ~Ancestor() = default;
    virtual const std::string& name() = 0;
};

class Parent : public Ancestor {
public:
    Parent() : name_("Parent") {}
    const std::string& name() override { return name_; }
private:
    std::string name_;
};

class Child : public Parent {
public:
    Child() : name_("Child") {}
    const std::string& name() override { return name_; }
private:
    std::string name_;
};

std::shared_ptr<Ancestor> CreateChild() { return std::make_shared<Child>(); }

std::string GetChildName() {
    std::shared_ptr<Ancestor> a = std::make_shared<Child>();
    return a->name();
}

PYBIND11_MODULE(example, m) {
    py::class_<Ancestor>(m, "Ancestor").def_property_readonly("name", &Ancestor::name);
    m.def("create_child", &CreateChild);
    m.def("get_child_name", &GetChildName);
}
```

```python
>>> import example
>>> child = example.create_child()
>>> child.name
'Parent'  # ???
>>> child.name
MemoryError
>>> Ctrl-D
[6]    6442 segmentation fault  python
````

As a comparison, `get_child_name` correctly works:

```python
>>> import example
>>> example.get_child_name()
'Child'
```

## Issue description

In a multiple inheritance scenario, the implicit up-cast from derived type to base type does not work when using a user defined smart pointer (i.e. holder) type of a derived class.

In case of using std::shared_ptr, or when inheriting only from one base class, the issue is not present.

The example works in C++, but does not work in python. Implicit cast definition in the python wrapping code does not help (declare it for C->A and C->B). Can not declare implicit cast between holder types.

## C++ code
```c++
template< typename T >
class MyHolder
{
public:
    explicit MyHolder( T* ptr = nullptr ) : ptr_( ptr ) {}
    template< typename U > MyHolder( MyHolder< U > ptr ) : ptr_( dynamic_cast< T* >( ptr.get() ) ) {}
    T* get() { return ptr_; }
    T* operator-> () const { return ptr_; }
private:
    T* ptr_;
};


class A
{
public:
    virtual ~A() = default;
    virtual void foo() = 0;
};

class B
{
public:
    virtual ~B() = default;
    virtual void bar() = 0;
};

class C : public A, public B
{
public:
    C() = default;
    virtual void foo() override
    {
        std::cout << "foo" << std::endl;
    }
    virtual void bar() override
    {
        std::cout << "bar" << std::endl;
    }
};

void testA( MyHolder< A > ptr )
{
    ptr->foo();
}

void testB( MyHolder< B > ptr )
{
    ptr->bar();
}
```
## Wrapping code
```c++
PYBIND11_DECLARE_HOLDER_TYPE( T, MyHolder< T >, true );

PYBIND11_MODULE( test, m )
{
    pybind11::class_< A, MyHolder< A > >( m, "A" )
        .def( "foo", &A::foo );

    pybind11::class_< B, MyHolder< B > >( m, "B" )
        .def( "bar", &B::bar );

    pybind11::class_< C, MyHolder< C >, A, B >( m, "C" )
        .def( pybind11::init<>() );

    m.def( "testA", &testA );
    m.def( "testB", &testB );
}
```
## C++ test code
```c++
int main()
{
    auto c = std::unique_ptr< C >( new C() );
    auto ptr = MyHolder< C >( c.get() );
    testA( ptr );
    testB( ptr );
    return 0;
}
```
